The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports let out by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead.  Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz derives in large part from his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual abilities of band members. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called on the particular style of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington’s mastery of the individual players’ sound, as well as how they fit together in a growing ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.
The Grove Music dictionary, in discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call in reference to using voice “as a jazz instrument” throughout his career.  This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do‭? ‬Are there restrictions or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change‭? ‬Although in‭ ‬1917‭ ‬D’Arcy Thompson stated that‭ “‬Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms‭” ‬the same can be said today. More recently,‭ ‬mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny‭ (‬e.g.,‭ ‬Raup and Stanley,‭ ‬1981‭)‬. Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic change in Prunum,‭ ‬in combination with experimental studies,‭ ‬can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters that could in turn be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell‭ (‬Stone,‭ ‬1995‭)‬. We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could be used to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies in order to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure that is a tube that travels over time through‭ ‬360‭ ‬degrees of space.  These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls,‭ ‬which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis.  This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary,‭ ‬and a continuous line separates each whorl and is referred to as a suture.  In most shells,‭ ‬the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl‭ (‬body whorl‭)‬.  ‭ ‬The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical,‭ ‬basal,‭ ‬apertural and abapertural views. ‭(‬The‭ "‬usual‭" ‬orientation of a shell is an apertural view,‭ ‬with the aperture toward the viewer and with the apex pointing up.‭)‬

A method for counting whorls is seen below.  First,‭ ‬the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins.  A line can be then drawn dividing the shell into two parts.  Whorls are counted from this line,‭ ‬and are estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal accretes‭ (‬i.e. builds‭) ‬its shell.  It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented.  Once a mathematical formulation is made,‭ ‬it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia remained rather static for the last ten years.  While the country is on track to meet many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as the water and sanitation targets, the rates of improvement for child and maternal health are woefully short of the improvements needed to meet their target goals by 2015.  The multiple reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, and point to a need to strengthen the health system rather than focus on programmatic interventions.
	Indonesia has made improvements in the number of births with a skilled health worker attending, with 72% of births now meeting this target.  That being said, this category still includes traditional workers, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions should the pregnancy be complicated (hence the large percentage of maternal deaths caused by hemorrhage).  In other words,  the improvements made in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading and there is still much work to be done.  In addition, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five years treated by a health professional.  While data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also of concern, with low rates across the country.
	Cesarian-section rates are still lower than should be expected, around 4%.  The c-section rates additionally point to another concerning issue.  While the rate of c-section is 7% in urban settings, it is only 2% in rural.  This points to the problem of equity of coverage across the country.  Clearly access to healthcare services is focused around urban areas.  Another issue of access concerns vertical equity.  There is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles.  Clearly the poor are finding it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out of pocket costs.
	In discussing next steps towards improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most basic question is how to most effectively address the lack of service.  Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre and post-pregnancy care for the mother and child.  There is no question that programmatic approaches to solve the problems outlined above are attractive.  Not only do “vertical approaches” that target one sector of improvements have much more targeted, manageable objectives, they also generally generate faster results.  There are some drawbacks to keep in mind, however.  One major drawback is that investing heavily in programming for one particular area of the health sector often means that funding for other areas suffers and human resources will flock towards working in that area that has more resources (the effect of international funding to HIV/AIDS and its effect on the family planning sector is one example).  In addition, running multiple parallel programs for one area results in duplication of services that are also uncoordinated between programs.  This leads to an increase in forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

In aspiring for a career in social work, I aim to join the Division of Family and Children Services to assist kids who've faced abuse or neglect; I also want to support troubled families. My contributions to the social work field would include: service, respect, ethical standing, and a dedication to fostering better relationships and continuously improving my own professional skills. These principles aren't just key for social workers; they are personal values for me.

I've always yearned to help others, yet I was uncertain of the right career path. Throughout high school and college, I witnessed folks shying away from problems in denial and using ineffective coping methods. These situations inspired me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still uncertain of a career path, I took a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, a friend introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy visiting her, nervous and seeking refuge from his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he'd called the police. To offer help, I visited his parents' residence. I privately shared my concerns with the police, who then asked me to speak with the parents since legal options were limited. The parents seemed anxious and claimed their son was ‘manipulative.’ This experience sparked my serious consideration of a social work career to assist families dealing with ‘simple’ disputes.

A crucial value for social work is social justice. Our society proclaims the importance of the individual yet often follows archaic traditions rather than true uniqueness. If we mourn lost individuals, why strive to be like ‘everyone else’? I uphold individuality and have protested social injustice throughout my schooling: changing my hair color, dressing uniquely, piercing ears beyond tradition, joining GSBA, and combating racism and discrimination. I'll keep fighting for social justice.

The following paper explores the Biological and Sociocultural models as they relate to insomnia. The Biological model delves into genetic information that is passed down through inheritance, along with various medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural model, on the other hand, examines environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review examines these models and explains each piece of research chosen to further clarify and connect them. The strengths and weaknesses of the research findings are then critically evaluated.

A sleep disorder can be categorized into several types: Primary sleep disorders, those related to another mental disorder, or those related to other issues. Primary sleep disorders are Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while those related to mental disorders fall under Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other sleep disorders can be caused by medical complications or the intake of substances. Dyssomnias like Primary Insomnia and Primary Hypersomnia represent complications in adequate or maintained sleep, and Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM episodes. Parasomnias, on the other hand, are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities or physiological occurrences. These include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). The review primarily focuses on insomnia and general primary sleep disorders in relation to the Biological and Sociocultural models.

The Biological model of sleep disorders centers around genes, heritable factors, and the physiological aspects of these disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are crucial for regulating sleep and wakefulness. A study involving mice found that there are specific GABAB receptors on orexin neurons responsible for these sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAB receptor promotes sleep, while its inhibition can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist baclofen increased sleep time in the study (Matsuki et al., 2009). This suggests that animal models like mice can be generalized to human studies, highlighting a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence of this receptor could impair adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implications are that if this phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and any alteration of the receptor could naturally disturb sleep, impacting everyday activities like school, career, and tasks requiring focus

This paper tackles three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). It begins by explaining what the condition is, followed by the process of diagnosis, including common signs. Lastly, it offers ways teachers in mainstream classrooms can support students with CAPD.

CAPD, or Auditory Processing Disorder, refers to how the central nervous system (CNS) processes and uses auditory information. More precisely, it's about the brain's ability to process sounds it hears, such as separating words or distinguishing them from background noise. Those with CAPD can hear just fine but struggle with how their brain interprets what they hear.

The disorder's roots date back to the mid-1950s, known then as "auditory imperception" when researchers studied children with communication issues. Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari started testing these children in 1954, and Kimura introduced dichotic testing in 1961, providing a model for the brain's underlying processes. A pivotal conference in 1977 sparked further research on the topic.

CAPD can manifest in various ways: trouble locating sounds in space, difficulty distinguishing between sounds, trouble recognizing patterns, not being able to detect changes in speech, sounds getting blocked, and an inability to interpret sound clues or determine the sequence of auditory information.

To diagnose CAPD, experts observe listening behaviors and test auditory functions using tools like questionnaires, surveys, and specialized tests. There isn't a definitive test or cause for CAPD yet. Many tests present multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli, and more advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals and measuring responses.

Twelfth Night appears to suggest that while disguise can aid in sustaining long-term deception, it's crucial to eventually shed this new persona to avoid losing oneself. However, ending a deception can lead one to feel isolated. Thus, one must choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with others, knowing that some may react neutrally, while others may be offended by the deceit. The theme of deception in gender role reversal is particularly tricky, as it raises questions like: why does one feel compelled to adopt the guise of the opposite gender? In Viola's case, it's clear that her disguise serves as a protective measure. Having landed in a foreign land, she fears potential attackers and decides to pretend to be a man. This strategy works, but it also isolates her from women, denying her a valuable support network. What's more, she's so convincing that Olivia mistakenly falls in love with her, thinking she's Sebastian. “Here, my lord, Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) Additionally, Viola struggles with concealed romantic feelings between her and Orsino: “Boy, you’ve told me a thousand times/ You should never love a woman like I do.” (5.1. 260-261) Despite this, Twelfth Night may be seen as a portrayal of how deception can help uncover repressed emotions, especially with Olivia and Orsino. Some suggest that Viola/Cesario's appearance forces these characters to confront their subconscious desires. For instance, is Olivia drawn to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does she secretly have feelings for women? It's unlikely the latter, as Olivia seems more inclined to judge by appearance, as seen by her swift shift in affection from Cesario to Sebastian, and her newfound familial regard for Cesario/Viola: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

The harsh nature of German colonial rule, particularly in German South West Africa, has been well-documented, with notable atrocities including the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama peoples. However, it's important to note that colonial empires are complex and varied, and the German colonial empire was no exception. Educational efforts across different colonies were also diverse. For instance, when the British took over German East Africa (now Tanzania), they encountered a significant number of literate Africans. German colonial education in Cameroon and other colonies was also commended by contemporary writers.

In stark contrast, South West Africa (present-day Namibia) had a drastically different educational landscape. Unlike in East Africa, where the government actively promoted native education, in South West Africa, the task of educating locals was primarily left to missionary societies with limited government support. While the government invested heavily in the education of Europeans, establishing schools and regulating missionary efforts, the educational gap between Europeans and natives persisted. Even after German rule ended, this disparity remained. In other German colonies, there were substantial numbers of literate Africans, but in South West Africa, most remained uneducated and illiterate. Various factors, including social, political, and economic ones, contributed to this disparity. This analysis seeks to delve deeper into these factors, focusing on new research into the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards natives.

There's a plethora of literature on education in the German colonial empire, much of it in German and written during or shortly after the colonial period. Early works primarily described educational systems, while later English-language studies compared these systems and analyzed specific aspects. These studies highlighted significant differences between colonies. Cohen's work on education in South West Africa and East Africa is particularly relevant. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa accounted for many of the unique characteristics of its educational system.

Geographically, South West Africa offered a moderately comfortable climate, though much of it was arid desert. This attracted a European population that was relatively comfortable. By 1913, around 15,000 whites lived there, compared to the 5,336 in the next largest settler colony, East Africa.

The category of Popular Music has evolved significantly over the past 100 years to encompass a multitude of genres, making it challenging to enumerate them all. Most, if not all genres—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—have produced numerous sub and sub-sub genres. Notably, the Heavy Metal sub-genre of rock has become one of the most varied and expressive within popular music over the last 40 years. Its diversity stems from the early realization of the genre's flexibility, which has led to the creation of various sub-genres and further sub-sub-genres, continuing to this day.

Today, Heavy Metal has developed so many distinct sub-niches that it's difficult to pin down what defines it. It has absorbed themes from other genres, originating from somewhere and evolving into the metal movement we know today. To fully comprehend today's metal music, one must understand the metal movement's essence and why it's considered a movement rather than just a genre.

Heavy Metal is, in many ways, a movement defined by darkness. It can be seen as a "music of more" – more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. Less primitivism, more skill – metal bands showcase remarkable instrumental prowess. The genre is also heavily associated with drug use, particularly during the mid-70s psychedelic boom, where musicians created otherworldly records under the influence of drugs. It boasts dark, visceral qualities, which were quite new to the music scene, as much popular music lacked these darker emotional traits. Later generations of metal have also drawn inspiration from the dark, visceral elements prevalent in the Romantic Era. Lyrics, such as those from "Helter Skelter," exemplify the darker side of the movement.

These lyrics from "Helter Skelter" by The Beatles illustrate the darker side of the band. The song's up-and-down rhythm is interpreted as a drug-induced rollercoaster, marking it as one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song with similar themes, with The Beatles aiming to prove they could match the heaviness and darkness of their rivals. The song was released on "The White Album" to demonstrate this.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike masterpieces, Henri Rousseau was already crafting his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. In 1910, The Dream, one of his renowned Post-Impressionist paintings, showcased a woman marveling at her dreamland, but it also reflected Rousseau's own dreams and aspirations as a painter. His journey was one of internal conflict: should he conform to or mimic established styles to gain acceptance in the art world he admired, or forge his own unique path? To fully understand The Dream, one must first know Rousseau's life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, France, he was the son of a successful tinsmith and hardware dealer. Rousseau had no formal art training and was a gabelou, or municipal toll service employee, until he was forty. After losing his first wife and eight of his children, he found solace in painting. Unlike his contemporaries, he was a folk painter, dreaming of recognition and acceptance, much like the average members of his class. His late start and competition with other renowned artists added to his struggle. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon noted that while Matisse feared painting tritely, Rousseau longed to create conventional art that would earn him a place among the Artiste Français.

Many a wise mind has pondered the deep link between ethics and aesthetics, truth and beauty. I firmly believe there's a profound reason for this. As John Keats once wrote in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." While much of what we learn in life comes from education or experience, it seems we instinctually grasp ethics and aesthetics without such teachings. Both seek to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty aim to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than laying down rules for judgment or creation. Criticisms of art or morals can never fully capture its essence. Discussions about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for instance, may focus on elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these don't explain why it's considered good art. Instead, when discussing favorite works of art or literature, one often hears a phrase like, "There's just something about it" before a more complex explanation. I believe both art and morals possess this intangible quality, this "je ne sais quoi," making them transcendent. This connection between ethics and aesthetics is especially evident in literature. As McKean puts it, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality." Literature's ability to convey moral values is as integral as it is in life itself. Living inherently involves values, and literature is significant because it reflects these values.

Today's Germany is a powerful, unified country with a rich cultural tapestry weaving from the peaks of the Alps in München to the shores of the Baltic Sea in Kiel. This unique blend of culture is felt throughout Germany, from Köln on the Rhine, through the heart of the country, to the Saxon city of Dresden along the Elbe. Given its rich cultural heritage, it's no surprise that Germany as we know it today is a fusion of various tribes and sources.

Germania, the ancestral home of the Germans, has a debated origin story. Some scholars, like Tacitus, claim the name came from the Germanic tribe known as Tungrians, who were previously called Germans before crossing the Rhine to fight the Gauls. Julius Caesar, in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, used the term “Germanus” to distinguish between conquered Gauls and unconquered Germanic tribes. Others suggest the name might come from the Old English word "ger," meaning spear, or the Old Irish "garim," signifying loud, noisy people.

Tacitus, in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," wrote that he considered the Germans to be aboriginal and not mixed with other races through immigration or intercourse. He described the harsh conditions of Germania, with its wild landscape, harsh climate, and sullen inhabitants, making it an unlikely destination for those seeking to emigrate.

The Romans, though they did not initially settle in Germania, sent expeditions to trade with the Germanic tribes and sometimes led military campaigns. However, they mostly returned to their vast empire, leaving the Germanic tribes to live on the empire's borders.

Over time, these tribes began to appear in the middle of the first century, trading goods and skills, including serving in the Roman army.

Below me, I stared, my mind blankly processing the scene before me. Unanimated and silent, I studied the view with practiced detachment, yet refused to connect it to any abstract understanding. Thoughts flowed in and out like a river, leaving me with an almost liquid experience of the moment. I had bought an art instruction book, "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain," to learn how to draw. One technique in the book was to frame a picture within a square, simplifying complex scenes. Looking at the bowl of fruit on the table, I was too overwhelmed to apply this technique. Instead, I just stood there, awestruck. My hand gripped the pencil, muscles tensing and relaxing as I tried to capture the scene. The water was clear and smooth, but the package of brown waste refused to budge, stuck like a slug on the toilet's bottom. With a mop in hand, I frowned at the offending mess. Flushes came and went, as did my introspective moments. Then, I reached for the toilet paper and began wrapping it around my hand like a mummy, creating an oven mitt. Standing up, I slowly dipped my hand into the bowl, as if preparing a turkey for Thanksgiving.

Teenagers are perishing behind the wheel, and several factors are combining to create this deadly trend among young American drivers. The National Institutes of Health highlight that the teen brain is not fully equipped to handle the perils of driving due to its immaturity. Lack of experience is also a significant contributor, leading to more fatal accidents, rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.
Teenagers fare worse when accompanied by their peers, a common occurrence as anyone with a modicum of common sense knows. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center revealed a correlation between the age of passengers and traffic accidents.
California and other states have implemented provisional licenses to enhance teen driver safety, restricting driving hours and prohibiting other minors as passengers. However, these are merely temporary fixes. The core issue is that as a collective, young drivers are not adequately prepared to manage the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman suggests that even 18 is too young for an unrestricted driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research indicates a common desire among those under 19-20 to take risks for the thrill. Thus, delaying driving until this tendency abates is sensible. If we persist in licensing young teens to drive, we will continue to witness deadly accidents, and the death toll is likely to escalate in the next few years. By 2010, Baby Boomers' children will be eligible to drive, resulting in millions of new teen drivers hitting the road.
Legislation addressing this issue would be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue to offer driver’s education classes for future drivers, but no one under 18 could operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could precede a full driver’s license, with a specific number of practical driver’s training hours still required, based on the majority of states' current standards (in California, for instance, that number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). This legislation would be both reasonable and effective in protecting teens across the nation.
The proposed legislation is not a novel idea.

While browsing through the Library of Congress’s collection of early Edison films, I stumbled upon a series of fifteen trick films, created between 1895 and 1901. These films primarily utilize creative editing to create illusions. My study focused on describing the poetics of these trick films, as well as examining the unique features of the later ones. Generally, these trick films of the late 19th century were confined within a frontal proscenium, used no camera movement, and consisted of long and medium shots, adhering to the rule that one shot equaled one film. However, a few films from the early 20th century dared to break these rules by incorporating multiple shots.

One common aspect among these trick films is their filming within an interior set, framed by a frontal proscenium, with the camera remaining stationary. This was a common technique in early films, drawing inspiration from theater and vaudeville magic acts. Consequently, figures in these trick films typically moved side-to-side within the frame, rarely walking towards or away from the camera. For instance, in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), the actors enter from the right and move back and forth horizontally, with the camera not following them as they exit the frame.

This frontal proscenium style also resulted in long and medium shots being more common, with close-ups being virtually absent. This method mirrored the theater and vaudeville traditions, where the audience saw the entire performance at once, framed by the stage borders. Actors did not move towards the camera, so close-ups were never used.

Most early trick films followed the rule that one conceptual shot equaled one film, limiting their length to about a minute or less. This also restricted their dramatic or narrative potential, with many focusing on short vaudeville-style tricks like magic and disappearing acts, with minimal story. However, it’s important to note that in a trick film, a single conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not correspond to a single physical shot. A single "shot" could be composed of multiple joined shots to create illusions. Carefully examine The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), where the physical shot with Mary’s severed "head" begins, even though the whole film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate for Republican ideals. Although he primarily worked as an agriculturalist, his short stint in politics and his dedication to his profession shaped him into a steadfast champion of personal liberty and government. His commitment to agriculture was the cornerstone of his views on sovereignty, the Constitution, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor saw the United States as an excellent opportunity to establish an ideal system because there were no native traditions to hinder its creation, allowing for a government of self-rule. He strongly believed in the natural rights of man and their interdependence, arguing that denying any right diminishes the value of all. These rights should remain beyond the government's reach. He viewed the "state of nature" as a place where the fittest and most cunning prospered, but in civilization, this should not be the case.

To create such a society, Taylor believed a government must account for the inherent good and evil within man. He held rigid views on dualistic morality, stating, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human." He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism. He believed a government founded on these principles would function fairly regardless of its administration, which would invariably be led by greed and self-interest. Self-interest, he thought, was man's primary motivator, but it was only considered evil when it led to societies that exploited others. A good government was necessary to contain man's natural evil, and even then, it must be closely observed to prevent the introduction of bad principles.

Taylor, like many other staunch Republicans of his time, advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He sought a Federal government with limited rights and powers as explicitly stated in the Constitution. He understood that an extensive Federal government could become expensive and despotic. However, he believed a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous without reference to the writers' intent. He considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, because it more clearly described the country as a group of sovereign states rather than one nation.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a sharp drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was a bit disheartening, and it's tricky to pinpoint the exact reason. With the arrival of winter in a New England campus, there's a natural decrease in commuters who travel by bicycle or foot, which could account for part of the decline. December also signals the end of the fall semester, where everyone is busy wrapping up schoolwork and processing grades, possibly causing commuter logs to fall off the radar. Additionally, December ushers in the holiday season, leading to a month-long break for both students and faculty, during which many don't need to come to campus. Classes resume in late January, which aligns with the low number of logs observed. However, the February dip remains unexplained. One might speculate that any new initiative can experience an initial surge of enthusiasm followed by a natural decline. To counteract this, we organized the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special blitz campaign that boosted log submissions for that month. Thus, maintaining project momentum in the face of both seasonal and semester breaks was a significant challenge. Another hurdle for such projects is that people's love for driving their cars is deeply ingrained in our culture. Therefore, offering incentives to engage in alternative commuting methods is crucial. We distributed numerous prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, an independent bookstore, and even some larger chain stores. It would have been intriguing to see if even more substantial prizes, such as a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car, could have increased participation and engagement. The nature of the prizes didn't change throughout the project. If the prizes had gradually increased in value, it might have helped maintain enthusiasm. Gift cards seemed sufficient at the start, but announcing the addition of a couple of bicycles in December and a hybrid or electric car in January could have potentially increased participation and engagement.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a financial instrument designed to mirror an index, a commodity, or a collection of assets, but trades like a stock. This flexibility makes ETFs attractive, as they offer the benefits of index funds, such as diversification, combined with the advantages of stock ownership, like the ability to short sell or buy on margin. However, ETFs come with their share of drawbacks, including the need to pay commissions on each trade, similar to buying stocks. Additionally, one of the standout features of ETFs is the wide range of funds available. It's essential for smart investors to assess whether these benefits genuinely exist and to what extent. For this analysis, we'll examine the ETF IHF and compare its top 10 holdings to see if owning a single ETF offers comparable benefits to owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks. We'll also explore if there's a better configuration of these stocks that could yield a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

To simplify our evaluation, we'll focus on the top 10 holdings, which account for 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Here are those holdings and their respective percentages:

To gauge how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we'll calculate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return, assuming the portfolio consists entirely of these ten stocks in the ETF's established proportions. The calculations are presented in the chart below.

From the chart, it's clear that a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings yields a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. Additionally, the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF's overall Beta. These results suggest that a portfolio of the top 10 holdings could offer a higher return with a lower Beta. However, we must consider if the portfolios' means are statistically different from each other.

To determine if these portfolios differ significantly, we'll calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and normalize it to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation with that of the ETF IHF.

"Dream-land" is one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-claimed superior poems. In this work, Poe employs the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott links back to Virgil. Virgil used this term to refer to an island north of Britain, considered the edge of the known world by the Greeks. Although Virgil indeed utilized this term, some credit should be given to a more contemporary source, as Poe was particularly interested in German authors. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," highlights the similarities between their poems, concluding that Poe was emulating Goethe.

Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a notable writer, famous for his poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts— the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's death. Within the second part of "Faust," there is a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem recounts the tale of a king who loses his wife after she gives him a goblet as a gift. Driven to grief and despair, he drinks heavily and eventually decides to end his life, leaving the goblet to the sea. The character of the King of Thule and the description of the narrator in "Dream-Land" share striking similarities, possibly serving as a dark mirror to Poe's own grief and struggle with alcohol.

Poe references "Thule" twice in his writings. In "The Pit and the Pendulum," he uses the phrase "ultra Thule," and in "Dream-Land," he employs the term twice, framing the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark, lonely, and haunted by deceased friends, with a world devoid of color. These scenes echo the themes in "The King of Thule," where the king is consumed by grief, loneliness, and a loss of will to live. The poem reads as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's narrative.

Goethe was a notable author whom Poe would have known, even if only peripherally through his respect for Tennyson. Poe himself acknowledged his admiration for Tennyson when asked. Beyond his connection to Tennyson, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe's work through various reproductions and translations, given the widespread popularity of his works after the original publications.

Could a customer who suffered injuries from slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages if the store manager knew about the spill twice and didn't clean it for half an hour because he was having dinner? A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer's punitive damage claim. To win, Palmer must prove that Martin's actions were malicious, meaning he acted with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm. She can argue that Martin should have cleaned the spill, as multiple customers had been injured from slipping before Palmer's accident, despite knowing the risks. While Martin's actions might seem despicable, they are reasonable given the six slip-and-fall incidents in 2009. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee named Rich Wayne told Martin about the spill, but Martin was on his dinner break. At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, informed Martin again, and he still didn't clean it. At 5:30 pm, Palmer slipped and fell, sustaining a serious back injury. Palmer is suing D&D for damages, and we're considering a partial summary against the punitive damage claim. In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for breach of non-contractual obligations if the defendant acted with “oppression, fraud, or malice.” Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intending harm or, absent intent, conduct that's despicable and committed with a willful disregard of others' rights or safety. Courts have ruled conduct malicious when the defendant was aware of the probable dangers and deliberately failed to avoid them. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Almost four years ago, I delved into a course on Islam at CBC. The class sparked passionate debates about whether Islam is inherently hostile. This question feels increasingly pertinent today. Reflecting on the 9/11 aftermath, I've seen a shift in American mass media's perception of Islam and extremists, from hostility to an extreme form of tolerance. I doubt that in 2001, a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with a clear Muslim background, could have been plausible.

The Prophet's Biography, I find, is intriguing yet puzzling. According to historical accounts, Muhammad's life seems to contradict his portrayal in the biography. Past knowledge suggests he forced tribes to convert to Islam through conquest, but the biography depicts him as a misunderstood martyr, humbled by others until they saw the truth in his teachings.

Striking similarities between Jesus' ministries and Muhammad's 'miracles' catch my attention. The instance of multiplying mutton and milk for forty men is notable. This narrative style, I believe, aims to present Muhammad as a humble prophet, relying on truth and miracles rather than proving himself. Such attributions diminish Jesus' life and personhood, as if Muhammad is stealing his glory.

Moreover, many stories in the biography seem to serve as proof of 'witnesses' converting to Islam independently. However, many accounts are relayed thirdhand, diluting their credibility. These stories are less persuasive because they're not firsthand and appear more suspicious.

What bothers me most is attempting to elevate Muhammad to a godly, humble, wise, and gentle figure. History contradicts this portrayal, suggesting that Muhammad's rise to power was less gentle and more complex.

The teachings and beliefs that Jesus held during his life were quickly abandoned as Christian thought evolved after his death. When observed in broader terms, Christianity progressively distanced itself from its origins. Today, the world is witnessing a growing awareness and unprecedented forward-moving trend. While traditionalists persist and resist new ideas, they may not have enough influence to alter the collective. Among Christians, historical understanding will significantly increase in years to come. A desire will arise to differentiate added doctrines from Christianity’s core principles. This process may take generations or centuries, but the reversal of Christian history is inevitable. A movement will emerge, stripping away layers of doctrine, akin to rewinding time, until only Jesus' original teachings remain. When this trend permeates the United States and Europe, masses will worship as if living during Jesus' time, adhering solely to his ideas. The church, as an institution, will maintain strength, leading the way. However, theological uniformity will increase, reducing diversity. Between regions, denominations, and divisions, similarities will outweigh differences. History is filled with reversals; Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, which later became a Christian state. Similarly, our country shifted from African-American slavery to leadership. The upcoming reversal in Christianity will undo history and diversity. This process will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, not literally. What has transpired since Jesus' lifetime?

Looking back in history, we find only Judaism, the foundation for Christianity. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion by the time Rome controlled Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was divided: Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of common people.

The novel "The Jungle" by Upton Sinclair serves as a stark illustration of the inherent greed and self-interest of people. It highlights how individuals prioritize their own prosperity at the expense of others, never considering those less fortunate. Sinclair effectively portrays this through the factory owners and managers who strive for nothing but the expansion of their businesses, disregarding any obstacles or collateral damage. The text paints a vivid image of the detrimental effects of industrialization, as "the line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world". This smog and pollution, along with animal waste runoff, are indicative of the owners' apathy towards human and environmental well-being. The same callous disregard is evident in their treatment of employees, who are exploited for maximum profit, "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar". Workers are subjected to harsh conditions, lengthy hours, and sudden layoffs, all without any compensation or job assistance. The absence of protective laws or regulations allowed such mistreatment to flourish. The workers, laboring and living in such deplorable conditions, were effectively treated as slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many writers employ various tactics to evoke specific feelings or perspectives in their readers regarding pivotal subjects. F. Scott Fitzgerald deploys several of these techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. He oftentimes pairs adjectives with nouns that don't typically align to create a particular atmosphere. Additionally, Fitzgerald imbues symbols with meaning and reuses them for the same purpose. He employs this strategy with numerous colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald establishes significance for these colors, particularly white/gray, which he later uses to convey certain feelings about important elements.

[REWRITE]Fitzgerald's description of white/gray as uniformity, with white representing a touch of elegance and high society and gray signifying age and weariness, is evident from the beginning of the book. Daisy and Jordan are frequently referred to as "in white" (8), and everyone at Gatsby's party wears white, such as Nick in "white flannels" (41), Tom in a "white shirt" (36), and Catherine as "powdered milky white" (30). The only exceptions are when Nick observes Gatsby's party: "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald further underscores this by coloring mundane subjects with these colors: Nick goes "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), the names on Nick's timetable are "gray names" (61), and Catherine's apartment is "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses" (28). Simple or ordinary people and places are also described in white or gray: Daisy and Jordan shared a "white girlhood" (19), the "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, the "gray" Italian child (26), and the dog-seller as a "gray old man" (27).

Once Fitzgerald has established the meaning of white/gray, he utilizes these colors to signify unimportance or uniformity around certain subjects. This first applies to Daisy. After a prolonged absence of any notable usage of these colors, Fitzgerald portrays Daisy as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster"; readers start to perceive Daisy as less of a character and more like a uniform addition, an object of Gatsby's longing (74). Fitzgerald employs this technique repeatedly around Daisy to reinforce this uniformity, such as the "gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar" (18) and her "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is a hotbed of agricultural activity, thanks to its mild, sunny climate. Crops grown here include tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a robust market for organic community-supported agriculture in the area, with many local organizations having long waiting lists for organic eggs and milk. Organic farms often offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This type of operation can both benefit from government programs and improve habitat quality, allowing for farm tours and educational programs.   While organic farming has higher costs and lower efficiency than conventional farming, it promotes greater plant and wildlife biodiversity in the area due to the absence of chemicals. Additional efforts to benefit wildlife, such as planting cover crops and managing plant growth, may also incur higher labor costs. Therefore, a landowner in this scenario might seek financial help to maximize profits and habitat quality.   The land in question is a 160-acre parcel near the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It's a mix of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest. This area is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion and is home to over a hundred plant and animal species, many of which are endangered or declining. The land was once inhabited by Native Americans and later used for cattle grazing and wood production.   To explore viable options for a small farmer, I chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs for cost mitigation and wildlife preservation. As a model, I found an organic farm in the same area.

Culture plays a crucial role in any negotiation. It's not simply about what a culture is, but also what it isn't and what it signifies. Culture is diverse, not singular or uniform. Generalizations like “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating” are overly broad.
